defaultThese factors may not be coincidental. Reductions in demand 
defaultseem to
default be largely
default the unintended consequence of energy policies that (a) embed the competitive advantages (and pricing power) of the Big Six energy companies, and (b) impose costs on customers that are not always proportionate to the benefit. 
defaultDemand reductions appear to h
defaultave less to do with the intended effects of government policy. The increase in the number of deaths resulting from cold weather suggests that the reduction in demand is attributable less to improvements in efficiency than to reductions in comfort, thanks t
defaulto increasing discrepancies between costs and many people’s ability to pay.
default The Government may not want to take credit for this reduction in demand.
defaultThe Government’s intended approach can be characterised as “supply-push”, while the unintended effect can be
default characterised as “demand-pull”. 
defaultD
defaultemand
default reduction through “supply-push” is like pushing on a piece of string. One should expect a higher standard to be demanded if efficiency improvements are commissioned by the person that buys the energy than if they are
default installed to meet the targets of the company that sells the energy. 
default“Demand-pull” driven by high energy prices should result in less of a Rebound Effect, than “supply-push” driven by 
defaultredistribut
defaulted costs of installation.
defaultIf “demand-pull” were the deliberat
defaulte result of government policy to internalise externalities through energy taxes (e.g. carbon taxes and fossil-fuel taxes, Scandinavian-style), the Government would have a substantial source of revenue with which to assist the most vulnerable households and
default to cut taxes that create a greater drag on the economy (e.g. taxes on employment and productivity). 
defaultIt would also encourage the most cost-effective responses
default to the price incentive in each circumstance, whereas the Government’s approach of targeted subsid
defaulty is necessitated largely by their desire to encourage projects that are currently less cost-effective.
defaultUnintentional “demand-pull” combined with intentional “supply-pus
defaulth” is the worst of all worlds. H
defaultigh prices go partly to subsidising uneconomic technolo
defaultgies and partly to 
defaultincreased profits for the energy oligopoly.
