defaulttle gain to accompany the pain, and neither do businesses who are not allied to the Big Six.
defaultSee above. The wrong kind of progress, from the wrong kind of policy.
defaultUnlike the biomass power industry, the biomass heat industry provisionally supports DECC’s efforts to look more closely at the potential impacts of increased demand for biomass, and the associated intensification of production. DECC are asking 
defaultlegitimate questions, and need assistance from the renewables and forestry industries, to make the assumptions in their models as realistic as possible. 
defaultThat engagement is at an early stage. 
defaultO
defaultn 
defaultthe basis of 
defaulta recent presentation, DECC’s Biomass Emissions 
defaultand Counterfactuals
default (BEaC)
default model needs ignificant refinements in the embedded assumptions. Forever Fuels looks forward to assisting that refinement, and 
defaultwill encourage other members of the industry to do the same.
defaultNevertheless, the outline is clear, even i
defaultf the detail is not. Wood is a scarce resource. 
defaultThere is a limit to the amount that can be produced sustainably. Competing 
defaultdemand
default for that sustainable resource mean
defaults
default that an increased use for biomass may result in reduced availability for other uses.
default 
defaultInte
defaultnsification of production to increase the 
defaultavailable resource may have significant consequences for 
defaultthe carbon stock in the short- to medium-term (known as the “carbon debt” problem).
defaultIt is important to understand that the often-encountered, simplistic expl
defaultanation of the “carbon debt” problem is simply wrong. DECC’s
default BEaC model is looking into the
default genuine issue rather than the simplistic fallacy. Distinguishing between the fallacy and the genuine issue has significant implications for policy.
defaultThe fallacy
default compares the carbon released by burning the biomass harvested from an area with the amount of carbon that is absorbed by regrowth on that area
default. 
defaultBy this comparison
default, the concentration of carbon in the atmosphere 
defaultmay be
default increased
default in the medium-term
default. If we ar
defaulte 
defaultworried about climate-change tipping points
default, then the short-term increase
default appears significant.
defaultThe fallacy lies in treating this on a temporal rather than a spatial basis. The argument assumes that only the trees that regrow on the felled land will absor
defaultb the carbon that is emitted initially. That is not how forestry works. Forests are harvested in rotation. If the rotation is at a sustainable rate, the amount of carbon released from the harvested land each year is equal to the amount of carbon absorbed b
defaulty the rest of the land that is left to grow that year. There is no short-term increase unless the forest is harvested unsustainably.
defaultDECC’s BEaC model 
defaultconsiders a more subtle question: what 
defaultif the rate of harvesting is increased to meet an increased demand
default for biomass? The model relies 
defaulton work that 
defaultindicates that this can result in a 
defaultcarbon
default increase in 
defaultthe atmosphere and reduction o
defaultn the land. In effect, accelerated harvesting increases the carbon footprint of the marginal volume of biomass that is produced
default through the acceleration. 
defaultI
defaultn cases of strong acceleration,
default this increase 
defaultmay be
default so significant that 
defaultthis marginal volume cannot be considered sustainable from a carbon perspective.
defaultThe significance of the distinction between th
defaulte genuine and fallacious iss
defaultue
default is that the fallacy could imply that there is a problem with all biomass that is not produced on short rotation, whereas understanding the genuine issue clarifies that the problem is with the marginal volume that might be produced through intensificatio
defaultn above the sustainable rate of production. Under the fallacy, shortening the rotation cycle reduces the problem. 
defaultIn reality
default, shortening the rotation cycle 
defaultcan be
default the cause of the problem.
