defaultThe most significant factor highlighted by BEaC th
defaultat may need incorporating into sustainability guidelines, is the question of “carbon debt”. This could be incorporated by 
defaultasking forest managers to supply three pieces of information annually for the area of land under their management:
defaultThis information should be easily accessible to forest managers. It allow
defaults
default for simple calculation of the real “carbon debt” (i.e. calculated on a spati
defaultal rather than a temporal basis). This would also broadly take account of the “counterfactual use” issue, by allowing the benefits of non-energy uses to be taken into account in the calculation.
defaultWe have put this suggestion to DECC and look forward to 
defaultcontinuing the discussion.
defaultLocal air quality rules are the appropriate way to deal with the varying circumstances 
defaultagainst which emissions have to be considered. The failure of some urban areas to meet air quality limits, when there are few biomass boilers or CHP units in those areas, demonstrates that the problem lies elsewhere, particularly with vehicle emissions.
defaultHe
defaultat is an inherently local product. Distribution losses are too great to transport heat over long distances. It is also an on-demand product
default. S
defaulttorage losses limit the length of time that it is practical to store heat.
defaultSome people would like to work round th
defaultis, and the air-quality issues, by using electricity to transport the energy used to produce heat. This ignores the many ways in which electricity is an unsuitable heating fuel.
defaultThe solution is to use the appropriate technology in the appropriate location to produce combined heat and power
default 
defaultin a way that ha
defaults acceptable impacts on air quality. 
defaultSome
default 
defaultobjections to CHP could be countered by combining CHP, low-temperature district heating, and basic heat pumps to upgrade the distributed heat.
defaultDirect gas heating is a superior option to centralised generation and heat pumps, for the reasons explained above.
defaultBecau
defaultse the incentives
default are skewed
default to disadvantage them. The cost of installing CHP and district heating has to be recovered from the value of the heat. It has been UK government policy for decades to keep heat as cheap as possible (e.g. special VAT rates and pr
defaultofligate use of our North-Sea gas reserves). There is therefore little value in efficiency.
defaultDon’t promote different forms of domestic heating s
defaultolutions. Internalise the externalities and let the market decide which forms are most suitable in each circumstance. The cost of any government winner-picking is economic inefficiency and capital destruction. Scrap most of our energy interventions, and re
defaultplace them with a carbon tax
default and
default fossil-fuel tax.
defaultNo. The government should take fewer specific actions across the board. It is doing quite enough damage already.
defaultBecause heat pumps are not a suitable technology for the majority of heating requirements in the UK. We have an inefficient stock 
defaultof buildings 
default(
defaultbecause heat is cheap
default)
default. Heat pumps are primarily suitable
default for high-efficiency new-build properties, and we don’t build enough new buildings to a suitable standard. 
defaultT
defaulthe majority of our properties for the next 50 years
default will not be suitable for heat pumps
